There is a separate page for MusicPlayers.

Modes and setups to help you write and perform music:

* EmacsLive is a setup to help you run [http://overtone.github.io/ Overtone], "an open source audio environment designed to explore new musical ideas from synthesis and sampling to instrument building, live-coding and collaborative jamming" based on [http://clojure.org/ Clojure] and using the [http://supercollider.github.io/ SuperCollider] server

* [https://tidalcycles.org/docs/getting-started/editor/Emacs/ Tidal Cycles] and Emacs. "Tidal Cycles … is software for making patterns with code, whether live coding music at algoraves or composing in the studio."

* SuperCollider is a mode helping you to write !SuperCollider code directly

* [http://chuck.cs.princeton.edu/ ChucK] Mode by Kao Cardoso Félix, based on code by Mikael Johansson, is [https://bitbucket.org/kaofelix/chuck-mode available from Bitbucket]

* [https://github.com/repl-electric/sonic-pi.el sonic-pi.el] A Emacs plugin to enable live coding music in Ruby communicating with [http://sonic-pi.net/ SonicPi]

* [EcasoundMode]: Ecasound is a very flexible audio multichannel recording and mixing tool and comes with an Emacs mode

* [https://ccrma.stanford.edu/software/snd/snd/snd.html Snd] Several packages are available for controlling JACK from within Emacs, and the plain-but-powerful Stanford University Snd editor also includes a comprehensive Emacs mode

* [[Mosaic]] is a concatenative synthesis system and music sequencer with a spreadsheet-based user-interface
